{
  "doc_id": "38535",
  "text": "Concerning the metabolism related methanol release, [CITATION_1] found that methanol within the leaf is mostly produced as a consequence of the demethylation of the pectin matrix, a necessary step in the extension of the cell walls during plant growth. On the basis of the pectin content, [CITATION_2] distinguished between two major cell wall types with a high or low potential for methanol release. In particular graminoids of the family poaceae, to which the main forage crops belong, are low methanol emitters. Most other plants have cell walls with a higher potential of methanol release. To a minor extent, methanol can be the Published by Copernicus Publications on behalf of the European Geosciences Union. result of an enzymatic cleavage of lignin (see [CITATION_3] , and references therein), demethylation of DNA (see [CITATION_4] , and references therein) and protein repair pathways [CITATION_5] .",
